About

Consider:

  • A cohort of unrelated individuals and the linear regression framework;
  • An environmental exposure variable E with 2 categorical levels: exposed and unexposed;
  • Genotyped markers (SNPs) G available at genome-wide scale;
  • The analysis to detect gene-environment interaction GxE.

Two approaches to detect GxE

  1. A single regression on total sample testing of interaction effect term in linear regression
    • \(Z^2 = (\frac{\beta}{se_\beta})^2 \sim \chi^2_1\);
  2. Stratified framework of two regressions per strata (Randall et al. 2013);
    • \(Z^2 = (\frac{\beta_1 - \beta_0}{se_{\beta_1}^2 + se_{\beta_0}^2 - 2 r se_{\beta_1} se_{\beta_0}})^2 \sim \chi^2_1\),
    • where \(r\) is the Spearman rank correlation coefficient between \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_0\), calculated from the genome-wide results.

seem to show close equivalence in cohorts of unrelated individuals of large sample size (references?).

The intuition behind the stratified framework is analogy of taking the difference between two random variables, and the large sample size allows to approximate well the distribution of effects in stratas to the Gaussian.

Problem statement

How will the two test perform in a cohort of related individuals? The direct consequence is change from linear regression to mixed-effect linear regression.

While simulations are good to draw conclusions on a grid of parameters, one need some previous guesses on why some things might behave differently in comparison to unrelated samples. Our guesses:

  • Guess 1: Biased estimation of variance components might affect the mutual test performance.
    • Remember: the residual variance partially defines the power to detect the interaction effect.
    • The less variance is explained, the less power is expected.
  • Guess 2: Estimation of the correlation coefficient \(r\) might needs a different formula for the mixed model. The use of \(cov(\beta_0, \beta_1)\) for that might be inappropriate.

In this report

In this report we focus on Guess 1 and explore three modes of phenotype simulation:

  • famgen: int * G * E + (1|FAM) + (1|ID) + R;
  • fam: int * G * E + (1|FAM) + R;
  • gen: int * G * E + (1|ID) + R.

As a reference simulation, we generate phenotypes with no random effects:

  • no_random: Y <- int * G * E + R.

In the next report

In the next report we will address Guess 2. A possible way to go might be WLS.

gxefam R package

See github.com/hemostat/gxefam (a private repository).

Loading package:

load_all("~/git/hemostat/gxefam/")

A really toy example:

par <- gxefam_par(num_fam = 20, num_sim_null = 2, num_sim_alt = 2, sim_phen = "gen", fit = "relmatLmer")
par
 - num_total 100: num_fam 20, size_fam 5
 - num_sim_null 2, num_sim_alt 2
 - sim_gen 'rbinom_fam', sim_phen 'gen'; fit 'relmatLmer'
 - var_fam 0, var_gen 0.3; var_explained 0.3
 - int 0.1; freq_g 0.3; freq_e 0.3
run <- gxefam_run(par, verbose = 0, seed = 1)
run
 *** Input parameters ***
 - num_total 100: num_fam 20, size_fam 5
 - num_sim_null 2, num_sim_alt 2
 - sim_gen 'rbinom_fam', sim_phen 'gen'; fit 'relmatLmer'
 - var_fam 0, var_gen 0.3; var_explained 0.3
 - int 0.1; freq_g 0.3; freq_e 0.3
 *** Output ***
 - power: total 0, strat_uncor 0, strat_cor 0.5 (rho_strat 1)

Replication of previous result using gxefam

The simulation model here is famgen.

 *** Input parameters ***
 - num_total 2,500: num_fam 500, size_fam 5
 - num_sim_null 20,000, num_sim_alt 10,000
 - sim_gen 'rbinom_fam', sim_phen 'famgen'; fit 'relmatLmer'
 - var_fam 0.3, var_gen 0.3; var_explained 0.6
 - int 0.1; freq_g 0.3; freq_e 0.3
 *** Output ***
 - power: total 0.447, strat_uncor 0.296, strat_cor 0.358 (rho_strat 0.167)

Was it crucial to switch to Spearman?

The plot of simulation results for the case of using the Pearson correlation coefficient.

Answer: no. The simulation results are almost the same in comparison with that of Spearman.

Extension of previous example for several additional modes

Columns meaning:

  • power_total: the power at alpha threshold for the standard interaction test in total sample;
  • power_strat_cor: the power for the stratified test, corrected using estimation of correlation rho_strat;
  • power_strat_uncor: the power for the stratified test (uncorrected).
sim_phen power_total power_strat_cor power_strat_uncor rho_strat num_sim_alt alpha
no_rand 0.6566 0.6568 0.6577 -0.0020 10,000 0.05
fam 0.5716 0.4020 0.3547 0.1221 10,000 0.05
famgen 0.4468 0.3579 0.2961 0.1670 10,000 0.05
gen 0.3916 0.3449 0.2832 0.1608 10,000 0.05

Observations:

  • As expected, there is no difference between the two tests for no_rand.
  • The drop in power for related samples (fam, gen and famgen vs. no_rand) is likely due to gen component.
    • Otherwise, the drop for fam and gen vs. no_rand would be similar (it is not).
  • Having 2 rather than 1 variance components also might be an issue.

It is not clear what is a connection between estimation of variance components and estimation of correlation coefficient required for the stratified test. The next simulation fam_envfam helps to get some insights.

Under fam_envfam, the exposure variable E is generated with the same frequency 0.3, but all individuals within family have the same exposure status. That yields the correlation coefficient between strata close to zero.

sim_phen power_total power_strat_cor power_strat_uncor rho_strat num_sim_alt alpha
no_rand 0.6566 0.6568 0.6577 -0.0020 10,000 0.05
fam_envfam 0.3852 0.3864 0.3852 0.0042 10,000 0.05

The results show that there is no difference between the two tests. At the same time, it is not clear what was the reason of drop in power.

Power as a function of int

Power as a function of int and var_explained

Correlation between strata as a function of int and var_explained

Note that here we plot our estimation of correlation between stratas. There are clear two groups of simulations:

  • no_rand and fam_envfam with correlations next to zero.
  • fam, gen, famgen with non-zero correlations.

The point is that estimation of correlation for fam, gen, famgen might be not correct.
